Package home.generics.intervals

Class Interval<A extends java.lang.Comparable<A>>

java.lang.Object
Interval<A>
Type Parameters:
A - generic class for the bounds of the interval. Both bounds (upper and lower) must be of the same type
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Comparable<Interval<A>>
public class Interval<A extends java.lang.Comparable<A>>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Interval<A>>
This generic class handles pairs of objects, which are unknown to this class, since their behavior is independent from this class' behavior. The Interval class is supposed to handle different algebraic operations between the objects of type A and B. In this exercise the classes A and B must be the same type in order for the interval functions to make sense and work.

    • compareTo

      public int compareTo​(Interval<A> comparison)
      returns a series of numbers which depend on the relative position of the Interval with the comparison one
      Specified by:
      compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<A extends java.lang.Comparable<A>>
      Parameters:
      comparison - the interval which the current Interval object is compared to
      Returns:
      • -3 if the interval is smaller than the one which is compared with
      • -2 if the interval is detached from the other and goes to the left
      • -1 if the interval partially overlaps the other and the lower bound is on the left
      • 0 if the intervals coincide
      • +1 if the interval partially overlaps the other and the upper bound goes to the right
      • +2 if the interval is detached from the other and goes to the right
      • +3 if the interval is bigger than the one which is compared with
